<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-066-231 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 212 771</DOCID><JOURNAL>Aldus Magazine  Sept-Oct 1991 v2 n6 p14(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Second chances: with the help of the computer, two educationalprograms offer a fresh opportunity to succeed. (Work OpportunityCenter in Minneapolis, Minnesota and Cuyamaca College in El Cajon,California)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Curdy, Averill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Minneapolis' Work Opportunity Center is an alternative secondaryschool where students are given the opportunity to succeed throughvocational training and increased self-esteem.andP;  The computer labcontributes greatly to this in the areas of writing and desktoppublishing.andP;  By using computers, students overcome their fears ofwriting; by using PageMaker and Aldus Freehand, they can producepolished publications.andP;  Teachers feel that computers help create abond between them and students with whom other teachers havefailed.andP;  Cuyamaca College in El Cajon, CA, has a graphics artscertification program for disabled students which has been fundedby a grant from the state of California and donations from DEC andApple Corp. Students receive computer training which moves themrapidly up the ladder of responsibility from entry-levelpositions.andP;  The desktop publishing and design skills learnedincrease the disabled students' self-esteem.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cuyamaca CollegeEducationComputer LearningCareer GuidanceSecondary SchoolsColleges and UniversitiesComputer-Assisted InstructionCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>